---
import PitchDeck from "../../../layouts/PitchDeck.astro";
const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const heroImage = `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide1.jpg`;

const slides = [
  {
    kicker: "The Hook",
    title: "Ontario’s “big forest” that still feels big",
    body: `
      <p>Algonquin is the classic Canada postcard: lakes + piney ridgelines + that quiet, cool north-woods vibe. In early July it’s green, alive, and photogenic in basically every direction.</p>
      <p>This is an easy “home base” trip: one good hotel, then day-trips for scenic drives, light walks, and wildlife watching.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Big scenery without needing big hikes",
      "High odds of lakes, loons, and (with luck) moose",
      "Naturally crowd-diffusing: lots of water, lots of forest",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide2.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Canoe at Algonquin Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Algonquin park canoe).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Fit check",
    title: "Why it matches your travel parameters",
    body: `
      <p>You want cooler nights, crowd-avoidance, scenic drives, and light walks with strong photo ROI. Algonquin is a “choose your own intensity” park — a short trail can still look like a calendar cover.</p>
      <p>And it fits your “one base + day trips” preference for the 5-night core stay.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Crowd-avoidant by design (spread-out viewpoints, trailheads, lakes)",
      "Short interpretive trails available",
      "Wildlife + water + forest = the photography trifecta",
    ],
    note: "Realistically: the busiest areas cluster around the main corridor and peak times. Early mornings are your cheat code.",
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide3.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Canoe Lake in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Canoe Lake - Algonquin Provincial Park, Ontario 01).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Getting there",
    title: "The drive is part of the vacation",
    body: `
      <p>Plan: Hooksett → one intermediate night → Huntsville area for the 5-night home base → one intermediate night → home.</p>
      <p>Your “avoid highways” route screenshot is perfect for setting expectations and choosing an overnight that feels like a mini-getaway, not a forced march.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Two-stage outbound + inbound reduces fatigue",
      "You arrive with enough energy to enjoy day 1",
      "Makes the trip feel intentional, not rushed",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide4.png`,
    imageAlt: "Driving route from Hooksett NH to Huntsville ON",
    caption: `Your route screenshot (local asset).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Unmissable highlight",
    title: "Beaver Pond Trail: short, classic, and high payoff",
    body: `
      <p>This is the template for a “light hike with great returns”: it’s a <strong>2.0 km loop</strong> with excellent views of beaver ponds — a lot of nature density for not much walking.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Short loop, strong scenery",
      "Wildlife watching is often better in the morning",
      "Ideal pace for back comfort + photography stops",
    ],
    note: "Real talk: bring bug protection and don’t underestimate how much better the park feels at 7–9am.",
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide5.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Moose in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Moose in Algonquin Provincial Park).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Unmissable highlight",
    title: "Algonquin Logging Museum Trail: a quick culture hit",
    body: `
      <p>If you want a “museum-ish” experience without committing to a full indoor museum day, the Logging Museum Trail is a great option in the corridor.</p>
      <p>It’s a nice balance: nature walk + local heritage.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Adds cultural texture to the park",
      "Good “active rest day” option",
      "Breaks up the lake-and-forest rhythm",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide6.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Canoe on beach at North Tea Lake",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (North Tea Lake canoe).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Unmissable highlight",
    title: "Canoe Lake area: iconic water-and-pines photography",
    body: `
      <p>You can get “canoe country” visuals even if you never actually paddle. Docks, shorelines, and golden-hour light do a lot of work for you.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Sunrise/sunset reflections",
      "Loon calls if you’re lucky",
      "Low effort, high aesthetic",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide7.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Sunrise over Canoe Lake in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Canoe Lake in Algonquin Provincial Park).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Lodging strategy",
    title: "Home base: Huntsville area (comfort + amenities)",
    body: `
      <p>The “hotel that feels easy” matters: comfortable beds/seating, reliable internet, and a fitness room are not optional for you.</p>
      <p>Huntsville gives you services + dining while keeping you close to the park corridor.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Minimizes daily logistics",
      "Easier parking/dining than deep-in-park lodging",
      "Lets you choose early mornings without feeling stranded",
    ],
    note: "Real talk: book early for Canada Day week. The calendar does what it does.",
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide8.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Moose in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Algonquin Moose).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Crowd avoidance",
    title: "How to enjoy the park without the people",
    body: `
      <p>The move is simple: <strong>start early</strong>, take a long lunch break somewhere quiet, then do a golden-hour shoreline stop.</p>
      <p>This lines up perfectly with photography and also reduces stress load.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "7–10am: wildlife and empty trails",
      "Midday: relax, casual dining, recharge",
      "Evening: easy scenic stop + photos",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide9.jpeg`,
    imageAlt: "Cow moose in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Cow Moose in Algonquin).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Real talk",
    title: "Bugs, weather swings, and pacing",
    body: `
      <p>Early July can mean bugs in wet areas and real variability in temps. Pack layers, and treat bug protection like standard equipment.</p>
      <p>Also: this is a trip where you win by <strong>not</strong> over-scheduling. Two “anchor activities” per day is plenty.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "Bring layers for cool mornings / warmer afternoons",
      "Bug spray + head net (optional) = sanity insurance",
      "Aim for short trails and scenic stops, not mileage",
    ],
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide10.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Juvenile moose in Algonquin Provincial Park",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Juvenile Moose - Algonquin Provincial Park).`,
  },
  {
    kicker: "Decision slide",
    title: "If you want: lakes + forest + low-pressure days",
    body: `
      <p>Algonquin is the strongest candidate if the goal is “maximum nature, minimum friction.” It’s a place where doing less can still feel like you did a lot.</p>
      <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Extremely aligned with scenic drives, light walks, and photo-first pacing.</p>
    `,
    bullets: [
      "High scenery density",
      "Flexible walking intensity",
      "Comfortable home-base logistics",
    ],
    note: "Call to action: shortlist this if you want the trip to feel restorative, not performative.",
    image: `${baseUrl}/slide-images/algonquin/slide11.jpg`,
    imageAlt: "Canoe Lake at Joe Lake Portage",
    caption: `Image: Wikimedia Commons (Canoe Lake - Algonquin Provincial Park, Ontario 02).`,
  },
];

const subtitle =
  "Big-lake canoe country, interpretive trails, and calm-by-default pacing — ideal for scenic drives + light hikes.";
---

<PitchDeck
  title="Algonquin Provincial Park (Ontario)"
  subtitle={subtitle}
  heroImage={heroImage}
  heroImageAlt="Sunrise over Canoe Lake in Algonquin Provincial Park"
  slides={slides}
  backHref="/travel/"
  accent="hsl(150 80% 45%)"
/>
